## Find the node in the map closest to the input vector. This node is the best matching unit (BMU). Denote it by formula_6
## For each node formula_7, update its vector by pulling closer to the input vector: formula_8

The variable names mean the following, with vectors in bold,
* formula_9 is the current iteration
* formula_10 is the iteration limit
* formula_11 is the index of the target input data vector in the input data set formula_12
* formula_5 is a target input data vector
* formula_7 is the index of the node in the map
* formula_15 is the current weight vector of node formula_7
* formula_6 is the index of the best matching unit (BMU) in the map
* formula_18 is the neighbourhood function,
* formula_19 is the learning rate schedule.
The key design choices are the shape of the SOM, the neighbourhood function, and the learning rate schedule. The idea of the neighborhood function is to make it such that the BMU is updated the most, its immediate neighbors are updated a little less, and so on. The idea of the learning rate schedule is to make it so that the map updates are large at the start, and gradually stop updating.

For example, if we want to learn a SOM using a square grid, we can index it using formula_20 where both formula_21. The neighborhood function can make it so that the BMU updates in full, the nearest neighbors update in half, and their neighbors update in half again, etc.formula_22And we can use a simple linear learning rate schedule formula_23.

Notice in particular, that the update rate does &quot;not&quot; depend on where the point is in the Euclidean space, only on where it is in the SOM itself. For example, the points formula_24 are close on the SOM, so they will always update in similar ways, even when they are far apart on the Euclidean space. In contrast, even if the points formula_25 end up overlapping each other (such as if the SOM looks like a folded towel), they still do not update in similar ways.

